          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/lotr/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="0" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Chicago, Illinois 2/2/2002<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.17)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9813'>Andrew "Bee Boy" Sitte</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9813&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 4, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> On February 2nd I ran a Middle Earth sealed deck tournament here in Chicago.  At 9am that morning I headed for the train station to head downtown and pick up James, Luke, and Phil, who were coming in from the suburbs.  They arrived pretty quickly, and by 11:30 we were back, waiting for the rest to show up.  By just a little after noon everyone (10 people) had arrived, and I explained the format (1 deck, 25/25, 10 creatures) and passed out cards.  In addition to our local players, we had Chad Martin (4 hour drive), Doug Lund (3 hour drive) and Josh Grace (8 hour drive).  Andrew Shallue (3 hour drive) also showed up later.<br>
<br>
Everyone built their decks from one starter, 1 wizards booster, 1 dragons booster, and 2 boosters of their choice.  I was more than happy with my pull - most of my rares weren&#39;t very good, but Southrons alone made up for the rest.  3 Cave-drakes and 1 Dragon&#39;s blood, one of each lure, 2 Rivers, 2 Musters, Gloin and Oin, And Forth he Hastened, Scroll of Isildur, and Gollum (hey, an ally, unlike last time).  I had plenty of double-wilderness creatures, but almost no other creatures.<br>
<br>
Chad and Doug were taking a long time to build their decks, but they were finally finished and we were ready to go.  Chad decided to put Riddling Talk in his deck just for fun, not that it&#39;d ever pay off.<br>
<br>
Game 1 vs Brian Greenlee<br>
<br>
I don&#39;t remember too many details of this game.  From his first turn, he had Gandalf, Glorfindel with Cram, Faramir, Peath, and Kili.  I couldn&#39;t afford to throw my 10 prowess creatures at him since he could kill a couple pretty easily and still play stuff during his site phase, especially after Faramir got the Torque of Hues.  I wasn&#39;t rounding up as many points at first, and when Oin died it looked like I couldn&#39;t play Fellowship - but then I read the card, and realized Gollum counted.  I stored a gold ring and a hauberk, Mustered the Blue Mountain Dwarves, and caught up.  On his next turn, Faramir failed to remove his Lure of Nature and ran off with the Torque.  The points were made up quickly when Gandalf tapped to test a gold ring, and it turned out that Kili was wearing a Dwarven Ring.  Unfortunately for Brian, Gandalf died that same turn.  <br>
So, I was going to win, but to get a 5-1 or 6-0 I had to corrupt Kili.  I had pulled one of each lure, but my real corruption power came in the form of 2 Greeds.  I&#39;d never thought it was very good, but this tournament made me realize how great it is in sealed deck.  His only characters, Glorfindel and Kili, moved to Moria.  Greed on guard - and he plays the Book of Mazarbul on Kili, who already had Lure of the Senses on him.  If he&#39;d had to make a corruption check he&#39;d have needed an 11, but I didn&#39;t have a way to force one on him...<br>
I eventually got around to grabbing the Scroll, and on my last turn moved down to get the Southrons and called the council.  On his last turn, Kili ditched the lure, but then Glorfindel played a Sword of Gondolin, and Kili was Greed-ed away - though the roll wouldn&#39;t have been successful for the free council CC anyway.<br>
<br>
After round 1, I looked at the score sheets, and every game had been a 6-0.  So, Josh faced Luke, a local player, and the rest of us faced someone with the same TPs.<br>
<br>
Game 2 vs Doug Lund<br>
<br>
I&#39;d met Doug up in Minnesota - we hung out at his house after the tournament there, though he hadn&#39;t been at the tournament himself.  He&#39;d been sitting next to me during our first game, and he&#39;d been commenting on some of my cards, whereas I hadn&#39;t paid any attention to his game and didn&#39;t know what to expect.  His first 2 drafts were Glorfindel and Thrain - if he&#39;d stopped there, most of my creatures would have been worthless as he had a Cram or 2 also.  Then he drafted Kili and Damrod - yay, someone to kill.  Of course, he was using my dice, which usually roll very well.  His first turn he moved to Barrow downs, and played 2 Cave-drakes (1 was killed), Giant Spiders, and Giant, killing both scouts.  He still got an item, but burned Cram to do it.  On my first turn, my four characters moved to Barrow-downs too, and also faced 4 creatures - 2 Lesser Spiders, Wargs, and Giant.  I killed them all, rolling nothing under a 4 (and that 4 was when I needed >3).<br>
Doug tried using my dice for one more turn, but after rolling 2s, 3s, and 4s, he gave up and pulled out some burning eye dice.  My dice continued to roll very well for me - 11 seems to be their favorite number.  It&#39;s great for Middle Earth, but I pulled them from Axis and Allies - a game where the point is to roll as LOW as possible...<br>
I went around doing my thing - Doug got Gandalf first, and once again Gandalf was the first wizard I drew.  Luckily my other company is pretty competent.  When Pallando did arrive, he moved to Edhellond, facing a horrible Lure of Creation (I was relying on Vanishment to protect him).  Doug&#39;s Thrain grabbed Map to Mithril, and both Doug and I assumed he had to stay<br>
tapped for it.  He didn&#39;t, but we didn&#39;t know that - and so my 2 Rivers worked well for a couple of turns. <br>
Eventually his companies teamed up, but when Gandalf played The Mithril-coat, Thrain got Greedy - he and Glorfindel both needed better than a 5, and Thrain blew it, taking Glamdring, Map, and his own 3 points away.  On my next turn, my main company moved over and Mustered away one of his factions.  Pallando Marvel&#39;s Told-ed his Lure and moved to Southron Oasis, Vanishing along the way and Hastening Forth to play the Southrons.  Finally, on my last turn, I moved my guys to play the Scroll, and Pallando to Henneth Annun to steal his last faction.  Pallando moved first and got tapped by a creature.  I was still going to get a 5-1, but if I&#39;d been able to double my 8 faction points I&#39;d have a 6-0.  So, my other company moved to Dead Marshes, drawing the last two cards in my deck.  Shuffle.  I played a couple of short events to get them out of my hand, and realized that I only had 7 cards in my hand.  So, I shuffled and drew even though I didn&#39;t think it would make a difference.  Well, it did - one of the top 2 cards was And Forth He Hastened, and I 6&#39;d him.<br>
<br>
After 2 rounds, Andrew Shallue showed up, and we took a short break to let him build a deck and jump in with 9 TPs.  Josh Grace and James Vollmer also had 12 TPs, and random pairings put me against James and Josh against Andrew.  Josh&#39;s hazards had crushed his first 2 opponents, and they did it again - so whoever won between James and I would be playing Josh for the<br>
ring.<br>
<br>
Round 3 vs James Vollmer<br>
<br>
James started with Elladan, Aragorn, Boromir, and Annalena - another group of strong people.  On his first turn, though, he split Aragorn and Anna off on their own.  They did ok for a while, but Anna eventually died.  Elladan and Boromir moved to Lorien on the first turn, and met a Cave-drake.  Elladan whacked it, and then Boromir stepped up and laughed.  &quot;What are you gonna do?  Bleed on me?&quot;  *WHACK*  Yeah, actually the dragon did bleed on him, and Boromir melted.  Once Elladan was alone, he ran into a couple of Rivers, but eventually got Skinbark.  Aragorn didn&#39;t do much by himself, and ended up joining<br>
Pallando.  <br>
This was my only game where I had Gandalf, and he started at Edhellond to move to Southron Oasis.  The two hazards were a Lure followed by Slayer.  No way I was going to risk that - I tapped to cancel one and Vanished the other.  The next turn, my starting company moved to Thranduil&#39;s Halls and Gandalf stayed.  One card on guard for Gandalf, and Lure of Power played.  I&#39;m thinking it&#39;s another Lure on guard, and I didn&#39;t have And Forth for Gandalf to both Marvels Told and influence.  I did, however, have a Muster, so Gloin brought in the Wood-elves, Thranduil MT&#39;d the LoP, and Gandalf brought in the Southrons.<br>
I called with 25 points, and James had 9 with no factions.  Elladan had been Rivered at Glittering Caves, so I figured he&#39;d get 2 points at least. <br>
Pallando, Aragorn, and a scrub played Master of Esgaroth and moved to Dale.  A creature tapped Aragorn and the scrub, and then I played River.  He tapped Pallando for the River and moved again.  I couldn&#39;t do anything to single wilderness or Border-hold (he moved to Lake-town) but I didn&#39;t think I needed to.  Of course, he And Forth He Hastened and played Men of<br>
Northern Rhovanion, getting 13 points and stopping my faction doubling.<br>
<br>
So, I was at 17 and Josh was at 18, so in the final round we&#39;d be playing.  The next person in line was James, with 13 points, so unless someone dunked either Josh or I would win.  Andrew Shallue actually had everything he needed to do it - his only test was a Test of Lore though...<br>
<br>
Round 4 vs Josh Grace<br>
<br>
Josh had crushed all of his previous opponents, so I knew I had to play it safe to have a chance.  In the draft, Thranduil bounced.  Gildor is the only other ranger in that fixed pack, so he bounced also.  A few more characters bounced, and eventually I was left with Gloin, Oin, Imrahil, and Haldir, while he had Erkenbrand, Hama, Robin, and Eomer.  On his first turn, I threw a bunch of creatures at him on the way to Lorien.  He rolled 3s, 4s, and 5s while I rolled 9s, 10s, and 11s, and only Erkenbrand and a tapped Hama made it to the haven.  He grumbled and put his dice out of the way, choosing to use mine.  On my turn, he hit me with a few creatures and some corruption, but I passed the Lure of Nature checks (>4) and killed or tied all the creatures.  I rolled 4 11s that turn, and Josh tried to switch my dice for his when I wasn&#39;t looking.<br>
Josh played Thranduil and Gandalf first, while I played Pallando and moved to Lorien (which I was very scared to do).  I  stuck a Lure of Nature on Thranduil on his way to his house where he played the Wood-elves, and then a Lure of the Senses on his way to Wellinghall.  He passed all of the checks, and played Quickbeam.  I was succeeding in keeping his other characters pretty inactive with 2 Rivers and an occasional creature, but they eventually grabbed Goldberry.<br>
I played a Fellowship, moved everyone to Wellinghall with a Vanishment and And Forth he Hastened in hand.  Pallando stole Thranduil, dumping Quickbeam, and breaking the Fellowship.  The next turn, he and Thranduil went to the halls to steal the Wood-elves, while the rest went to Dead Marshes.  Haldir was finally corrupted away after his 10th or so corruption check - he was bearing a cloak and Lure of Nature pretty much the entire game, and Lure of the Senses for some of it, and Josh attacked with Corpse-candle and played Weariness of the Heart a couple of times too.  Imrahil got a Sword of Gondolin.<br>
On my last turn, Gloin/Imrahil/Oin/Gollum all moved to Southron Oasis, while Pal/Thran moved to Moria.  I had to get one of them to call, but then I cycled so I could call anyway.  On the way to Southron Oasis, Josh dropped 2 Rivers.  So much for that...but then he took one back, and played Wargs.  Imrahil killed his, and Gloin did it untapped with the shield&#39;s help.  Josh decided to save the River for Pallando, and played Trolls of the Far Harad instead  - which I Dark Quarreled.  Pallando and Thranduil moved, and Josh played Itangast Ahunt and Doors of Night, but all it took was a Twilight to deal with it.  Pallando Vanished the attack, and Thranduil played the Scroll while Oin tapped for the River so Gloin could Muster the Southrons.  I ended up drawing both Rivers again, and they were enough to stop Josh on his last turn.<br>
<br>
During one of Josh&#39;s organization phases, I heard a voice say &#39;I play Riddling Talk&#39; and looked over to see Chad grinning at me.  I ran over to the table - he needed >8 to riddle the Ambusher, and rolled a 10.  Then he needed to guess a card...with his opponent playing the same fixed pack as me, and one of the 2 factions on the table, I would have guessed the other<br>
- Wood-elves - but Chad guessed Risky Blow, which wasn&#39;t there (Wood-elves were).<br>
<br>
More fun stuff from the tournament: Chad&#39;s starting company was Elrond, Glorfindel, and Bergil.  Through 4 rounds, Elrond and Glorfindel both died at least once, but Bergil never did.  Drew&#39;s Mouth of Sauron killed Thrain, even with Risky Blow.  Luke played From the Pits of Angband with Doors of Night in play, saw Josh return Smaug Ahunt and Cave Worm to his hand, and then moved to Ovir Hollow.  Josh drew Itangast Ahunt as well.  Ooof.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I won a tournament with more than 4 people for the first time.  Josh came in second, Doug Lund in 3rd, and James Vollmer in 4th (they both had 15 but Doug won their game).  I won a Gollum Gold ring, and everyone else chose their prizes in order (Lidless Eye packs, set of 9 German Promos, box of Dragons, etc).  Brian Greenlee got 2 packs of Lidless Eye and pulled The One Ring.  <br>
<br>
Afterwards, I dropped James, Luke, and Phil off at Union Station and then met Chad, Pam, Josh, Doug, and Andrew at Giordano&#39;s for dinner.  We all went back to my apartment to continue our conversation, and ended up talking until around 6 am (Josh left at 11, Chad and Pam at 4:30, and Doug and Andrew stayed over)<br>
<br>
Whew!  A thoroughly exhausting day that was more than worth it!<br>
<br>
Andrew Sitte<br>
One February 2nd I ran a Middle Earth sealed deck tournament here in Chicago.  At 9am that morning I headed for the train station to head downtown and pick up James, Luke, and Phil, who were coming in from the suburbs.  They arrived pretty quickly, and by 11:30 we were back, waiting for the rest to show up.  By just a little after noon everyone (10 people) had arrived, and I explained the format (1 deck, 25/25, 10 creatures) and passed out cards.  In addition to our local players, we had Chad Martin (4 hour drive), Doug Lund (3 hour drive) and Josh Grace (8 hour drive).  Andrew Shallue (3 hour drive) also showed up later.<br>
<br>
Everyone built their decks from one starter, 1 wizards booster, 1 dragons booster, and 2 boosters of their choice.  I was more than happy with my pull - most of my rares weren&#39;t very good, but Southrons alone made up for the rest.  3 Cave-drakes and 1 Dragon&#39;s blood, one of each lure, 2 Rivers, 2 Musters, Gloin and Oin, And Forth he Hastened, Scroll of Isildur, and Gollum (hey, an ally, unlike last time).  I had plenty of double-wilderness creatures, but almost no other creatures.<br>
<br>
Chad and Doug were taking a long time to build their decks, but they were finally finished and we were ready to go.  Chad decided to put Riddling Talk in his deck just for fun, not that it&#39;d ever pay off.<br>
<br>
Game 1 vs Brian Greenlee<br>
<br>
I don&#39;t remember too many details of this game.  From his first turn, he had Gandalf, Glorfindel with Cram, Faramir, Peath, and Kili.  I couldn&#39;t afford to throw my 10 prowess creatures at him since he could kill a couple pretty easily and still play stuff during his site phase, especially after Faramir got the Torque of Hues.  I wasn&#39;t rounding up as many points at first, and when Oin died it looked like I couldn&#39;t play Fellowship - but then I read the card, and realized Gollum counted.  I stored a gold ring and a hauberk, Mustered the Blue Mountain Dwarves, and caught up.  On his next turn, Faramir failed to remove his Lure of Nature and ran off with the Torque.  The points were made up quickly when Gandalf tapped to test a gold ring, and it turned out that Kili was wearing a Dwarven Ring.  Unfortunately for Brian, Gandalf died that same turn.  <br>
So, I was going to win, but to get a 5-1 or 6-0 I had to corrupt Kili.  I had pulled one of each lure, but my real corruption power came in the form of 2 Greeds.  I&#39;d never thought it was very good, but this tournament made me realize how great it is in sealed deck.  His only characters, Glorfindel and Kili, moved to Moria.  Greed on guard - and he plays the Book of Mazarbul on Kili, who already had Lure of the Senses on him.  If he&#39;d had to make a corruption check he&#39;d have needed an 11, but I didn&#39;t have a way to force one on him...<br>
I eventually got around to grabbing the Scroll, and on my last turn moved down to get the Southrons and called the council.  On his last turn, Kili ditched the lure, but then Glorfindel played a Sword of Gondolin, and Kili was Greed-ed away - though the roll wouldn&#39;t have been successful for the free council CC anyway.<br>
<br>
After round 1, I looked at the score sheets, and every game had been a 6-0.  So, Josh faced Luke, a local player, and the rest of us faced someone with the same TPs.<br>
<br>
Game 2 vs Doug Lund<br>
<br>
I&#39;d met Doug up in Minnesota - we hung out at his house after the tournament there, though he hadn&#39;t been at the tournament himself.  He&#39;d been sitting next to me during our first game, and he&#39;d been commenting on some of my cards, whereas I hadn&#39;t paid any attention to his game and didn&#39;t know what to expect.  His first 2 drafts were Glorfindel and Thrain - if he&#39;d stopped there, most of my creatures would have been worthless as he had a Cram or 2 also.  Then he drafted Kili and Damrod - yay, someone to kill.  Of course, he was using my dice, which usually roll very well.  His first turn he moved to Barrow downs, and played 2 Cave-drakes (1 was killed), Giant Spiders, and Giant, killing both scouts.  He still got an item, but burned Cram to do it.  On my first turn, my four characters moved to Barrow-downs too, and also faced 4 creatures - 2 Lesser Spiders, Wargs, and Giant.  I killed them all, rolling nothing under a 4 (and that 4 was when I needed >3).<br>
Doug tried using my dice for one more turn, but after rolling 2s, 3s, and 4s, he gave up and pulled out some burning eye dice.  My dice continued to roll very well for me - 11 seems to be their favorite number.  It&#39;s great for Middle Earth, but I pulled them from Axis and Allies - a game where the point is to roll as LOW as possible...<br>
I went around doing my thing - Doug got Gandalf first, and once again Gandalf was the first wizard I drew.  Luckily my other company is pretty competent.  When Pallando did arrive, he moved to Edhellond, facing a horrible Lure of Creation (I was relying on Vanishment to protect him).  Doug&#39;s Thrain grabbed Map to Mithril, and both Doug and I assumed he had to stay<br>
tapped for it.  He didn&#39;t, but we didn&#39;t know that - and so my 2 Rivers worked well for a couple of turns. <br>
Eventually his companies teamed up, but when Gandalf played The Mithril-coat, Thrain got Greedy - he and Glorfindel both needed better than a 5, and Thrain blew it, taking Glamdring, Map, and his own 3 points away.  On my next turn, my main company moved over and Mustered away one of his factions.  Pallando Marvel&#39;s Told-ed his Lure and moved to Southron Oasis, Vanishing along the way and Hastening Forth to play the Southrons.  Finally, on my last turn, I moved my guys to play the Scroll, and Pallando to Henneth Annun to steal his last faction.  Pallando moved first and got tapped by a creature.  I was still going to get a 5-1, but if I&#39;d been able to double my 8 faction points I&#39;d have a 6-0.  So, my other company moved to Dead Marshes, drawing the last two cards in my deck.  Shuffle.  I played a couple of short events to get them out of my hand, and realized that I only had 7 cards in my hand.  So, I shuffled and drew even though I didn&#39;t think it would make a difference.  Well, it did - one of the top 2 cards was And Forth He Hastened, and I 6&#39;d him.<br>
<br>
After 2 rounds, Andrew Shallue showed up, and we took a short break to let him build a deck and jump in with 9 TPs.  Josh Grace and James Vollmer also had 12 TPs, and random pairings put me against James and Josh against Andrew.  Josh&#39;s hazards had crushed his first 2 opponents, and they did it again - so whoever won between James and I would be playing Josh for the<br>
ring.<br>
<br>
Round 3 vs James Vollmer<br>
<br>
James started with Elladan, Aragorn, Boromir, and Annalena - another group of strong people.  On his first turn, though, he split Aragorn and Anna off on their own.  They did ok for a while, but Anna eventually died.  Elladan and Boromir moved to Lorien on the first turn, and met a Cave-drake.  Elladan whacked it, and then Boromir stepped up and laughed.  &quot;What are you gonna do?  Bleed on me?&quot;  *WHACK*  Yeah, actually the dragon did bleed on him, and Boromir melted.  Once Elladan was alone, he ran into a couple of Rivers, but eventually got Skinbark.  Aragorn didn&#39;t do much by himself, and ended up joining<br>
Pallando.  <br>
This was my only game where I had Gandalf, and he started at Edhellond to move to Southron Oasis.  The two hazards were a Lure followed by Slayer.  No way I was going to risk that - I tapped to cancel one and Vanished the other.  The next turn, my starting company moved to Thranduil&#39;s Halls and Gandalf stayed.  One card on guard for Gandalf, and Lure of Power played.  I&#39;m thinking it&#39;s another Lure on guard, and I didn&#39;t have And Forth for Gandalf to both Marvels Told and influence.  I did, however, have a Muster, so Gloin brought in the Wood-elves, Thranduil MT&#39;d the LoP, and Gandalf brought in the Southrons.<br>
I called with 25 points, and James had 9 with no factions.  Elladan had been Rivered at Glittering Caves, so I figured he&#39;d get 2 points at least. <br>
Pallando, Aragorn, and a scrub played Master of Esgaroth and moved to Dale.  A creature tapped Aragorn and the scrub, and then I played River.  He tapped Pallando for the River and moved again.  I couldn&#39;t do anything to single wilderness or Border-hold (he moved to Lake-town) but I didn&#39;t think I needed to.  Of course, he And Forth He Hastened and played Men of<br>
Northern Rhovanion, getting 13 points and stopping my faction doubling.<br>
<br>
So, I was at 17 and Josh was at 18, so in the final round we&#39;d be playing.  The next person in line was James, with 13 points, so unless someone dunked either Josh or I would win.  Andrew Shallue actually had everything he needed to do it - his only test was a Test of Lore though...<br>
<br>
Round 4 vs Josh Grace<br>
<br>
Josh had crushed all of his previous opponents, so I knew I had to play it safe to have a chance.  In the draft, Thranduil bounced.  Gildor is the only other ranger in that fixed pack, so he bounced also.  A few more characters bounced, and eventually I was left with Gloin, Oin, Imrahil, and Haldir, while he had Erkenbrand, Hama, Robin, and Eomer.  On his first turn, I threw a bunch of creatures at him on the way to Lorien.  He rolled 3s, 4s, and 5s while I rolled 9s, 10s, and 11s, and only Erkenbrand and a tapped Hama made it to the haven.  He grumbled and put his dice out of the way, choosing to use mine.  On my turn, he hit me with a few creatures and some corruption, but I passed the Lure of Nature checks (>4) and killed or tied all the creatures.  I rolled 4 11s that turn, and Josh tried to switch my dice for his when I wasn&#39;t looking.<br>
Josh played Thranduil and Gandalf first, while I played Pallando and moved to Lorien (which I was very scared to do).  I  stuck a Lure of Nature on Thranduil on his way to his house where he played the Wood-elves, and then a Lure of the Senses on his way to Wellinghall.  He passed all of the checks, and played Quickbeam.  I was succeeding in keeping his other characters pretty inactive with 2 Rivers and an occasional creature, but they eventually grabbed Goldberry.<br>
I played a Fellowship, moved everyone to Wellinghall with a Vanishment and And Forth he Hastened in hand.  Pallando stole Thranduil, dumping Quickbeam, and breaking the Fellowship.  The next turn, he and Thranduil went to the halls to steal the Wood-elves, while the rest went to Dead Marshes.  Haldir was finally corrupted away after his 10th or so corruption check - he was bearing a cloak and Lure of Nature pretty much the entire game, and Lure of the Senses for some of it, and Josh attacked with Corpse-candle and played Weariness of the Heart a couple of times too.  Imrahil got a Sword of Gondolin.<br>
On my last turn, Gloin/Imrahil/Oin/Gollum all moved to Southron Oasis, while Pal/Thran moved to Moria.  I had to get one of them to call, but then I cycled so I could call anyway.  On the way to Southron Oasis, Josh dropped 2 Rivers.  So much for that...but then he took one back, and played Wargs.  Imrahil killed his, and Gloin did it untapped with the shield&#39;s help.  Josh decided to save the River for Pallando, and played Trolls of the Far Harad instead  - which I Dark Quarreled.  Pallando and Thranduil moved, and Josh played Itangast Ahunt and Doors of Night, but all it took was a Twilight to deal with it.  Pallando Vanished the attack, and Thranduil played the Scroll while Oin tapped for the River so Gloin could Muster the Southrons.  I ended up drawing both Rivers again, and they were enough to stop Josh on his last turn.<br>
<br>
During one of Josh&#39;s organization phases, I heard a voice say &#39;I play Riddling Talk&#39; and looked over to see Chad grinning at me.  I ran over to the table - he needed >8 to riddle the Ambusher, and rolled a 10.  Then he needed to guess a card...with his opponent playing the same fixed pack as me, and one of the 2 factions on the table, I would have guessed the other<br>
- Wood-elves - but Chad guessed Risky Blow, which wasn&#39;t there (Wood-elves were).<br>
<br>
More fun stuff from the tournament: Chad&#39;s starting company was Elrond, Glorfindel, and Bergil.  Through 4 rounds, Elrond and Glorfindel both died at least once, but Bergil never did.  Drew&#39;s Mouth of Sauron killed Thrain, even with Risky Blow.  Luke played From the Pits of Angband with Doors of Night in play, saw Josh return Smaug Ahunt and Cave Worm to his hand, and then moved to Ovir Hollow.  Josh drew Itangast Ahunt as well.  Ooof.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I won a tournament with more than 4 people for the first time.  Josh came in second, Doug Lund in 3rd, and James Vollmer in 4th (they both had 15 but Doug won their game).  I won a Gollum Gold ring, and everyone else chose their prizes in order (Lidless Eye packs, set of 9 German Promos, box of Dragons, etc).  Brian Greenlee got 2 packs of Lidless Eye and pulled The One Ring.  <br>
<br>
Afterwards, I dropped James, Luke, and Phil off at Union Station and then met Chad, Pam, Josh, Doug, and Andrew at Giordano&#39;s for dinner.  We all went back to my apartment to continue our conversation, and ended up talking until around 6 am (Josh left at 11, Chad and Pam at 4:30, and Doug and Andrew stayed over)<br>
<br>
Whew!  A thoroughly exhausting day that was more than worth it!<br>
<br>
Andrew Sitte<br>
<br>
PS - If any of you LotR DeckTechers want to know about Middle Earth CCG, just send me a D-mail.  LotR is good, but MECCG is the best game I&#39;ve ever played. <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=3433&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
